│ stop({"edit_points": [[7342, 7355, "llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp"]],    │
│ "thoughts": "### 1. Understanding the Issue\n\nThe vectorizer is aborting due to an        │
│ assertion failure: `VPlan cost model and legacy cost model disagreed`. This assertion is a │
│ safeguard put in place during the transition to the new VPlan-based cost model. It ensures │
│ that for loops where no advanced VPlan-specific optimizations are applied, the new model's │
│ decision on the best vectorization factor (VF) matches the old (legacy) model's            │
│ decision.\n\nWhen the decisions differ, the function                                       │
│ `planContainsAdditionalSimplifications` is called to check if the VPlan contains           │
│ optimizations that the legacy cost model isn't aware of. If it does, the disagreement is   │
│ justified. In our case, the assertion fires, meaning the VFs disagree, and                 │
│ `planContainsAdditionalSimplifications` returned `false`.\n\n### 2. Analyzing the          │
│ Reproducer and Debugger State\n\nThe key part of the reproducer is this sequence inside    │
│ the loop:\n\n```llvm\n%0 = load i32, ptr %src.1, align 4\n%smax = tail call i32            │
│ @llvm.smax.i32(i32 %0, i32 0)\n%umin = tail call i32 @llvm.umin.i32(i32 %smax, i32         │
│ 1)\n%umin.ext = zext i32 %umin to i64\n%gep.src.2 = getelementptr i8, ptr %src.2, i64      │
│ %umin.ext\n%1 = load i8, ptr %gep.src.2, align 1\n```\n\nThe address for the `load` from   │
│ `%src.2` depends on a `load` from `%src.1`. Since `%src.1` is a loop-invariant pointer,    │
│ the value loaded from it (`%0`) is the same in every iteration. Consequently, all          │
│ instructions depending on it (`%smax`, `%umin`, `%umin.ext`, `%gep.src.2`) are also        │
│ loop-invariant. We call these \"uniform\".\n\nThe VPlan infrastructure is smart enough to  │
│ recognize this. It models these instructions as `VPInstruction::VPWiden` with a            │
│ `isUniform()` property, meaning they don't need to be widened into vector instructions;    │
│ the scalar value can be broadcasted. This is a significant optimization.\n\nThe legacy     │
│ cost model, however, is not as sophisticated. It sees the `getelementptr` with a           │
│ non-induction-variable index and conservatively assumes it's a gather operation, which is  │
│ expensive. It therefore concludes that vectorization is not profitable and chooses a VF of │
│ 1 (i.e., no vectorization).\n\nThe VPlan cost model, aware of the uniform nature of the    │
│ GEP index, calculates a much lower cost and decides that vectorizing with a factor of 4 is │
│ profitable.\n\nThis leads to the disagreement:\n*   **Legacy VF**: 1\n*   **VPlan VF**:    │
│ 4\n\n### 3. Root Cause Analysis\n\nThe root cause is that                                  │
│ `planContainsAdditionalSimplifications` does not consider the presence of `isUniform()`    │
│ instructions in the VPlan as an \"additional simplification.\" The function primarily      │
│ checks for dead code (`I->isDead()`). Since the uniform instructions are not dead, the     │
│ function returns `false`, and the assertion is incorrectly triggered.\n\nThe VPlan's       │
│ ability to identify and hoist uniform instructions is a clear optimization that the legacy │
│ model cannot account for. Therefore, we should teach                                       │
│ `planContainsAdditionalSimplifications` to recognize this situation.\n\n### 4. Proposed    │
│ Edit Point(s)\n\nThe fix is to update `planContainsAdditionalSimplifications` to iterate   │
│ through the recipes in the VPlan and return `true` if any of them are uniform. This        │
│ correctly informs the assertion that the VPlan has performed an optimization beyond the    │
│ legacy model's capabilities, thus justifying the different VF choice.\n\n**File**:         │
│ `llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp`\n\n```cpp\n// Edit starting at line      │
│ 7342\nbool LoopVectorizationPlanner::planContainsAdditionalSimplifications(\n    const     │
│ VPlan &Plan, const VPCostContext &CostCtx, Loop *OrigLoop) {\n  // First, check for any    │
│ dead instructions.\n  for (const VPBlockBase *VPB : Plan.getVPBlocks()) {\n    for (const  │
│ VPRecipeBase &R : *VPB) {\n      if (auto *I = dyn_cast<VPInstruction>(&R)) {\n        if  │
│ (I->isDead())\n          return true;\n      }\n    }\n  }\n\n  // Second, check if the    │
│ VPlan contains uniform instructions. These are not\n  // modeled by the legacy cost model, │
│ so we should allow the VPlan cost model\n  // to make a different decision.\n  for (const  │
│ VPBlockBase *VPB : Plan.getVPBlocks())\n    for (const VPRecipeBase &R : *VPB)\n      if   │
│ (R.isUniform())\n        return true;\n\n  return false;\n}\n```\n\n### 5.                 │
│ Conclusion\n\nBy making `planContainsAdditionalSimplifications` aware of uniform           │
│ instructions, we correctly account for a known difference in modeling capabilities between │
│ the VPlan and legacy cost models. This resolves the incorrect assertion failure and allows │
│ the vectorizer to proceed with the more profitable vectorization plan identified by the    │
│ VPlan cost model."})                                                                       │
